{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VRhQRvFugrHhHfJ5BXZyks","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# CLAUDE.md\n     2→\n     3→This file provides guidance to Claude Code (claude.ai/code) when working with code in this repository.\n     4→\n     5→## Repository Overview\n     6→\n     7→Office-Bohemia is the primary repository for Microsoft Loop, built on the Fluid Framework for real-time collaboration. It's a Yarn-based monorepo (~200 packages) using Lage for task orchestration.\n     8→\n     9→## Documentation\n    10→\n    11→Detailed documentation lives in `./docs/`. Key sections:\n    12→\n    13→- `docs/developer-guide/` - Internal development docs\n    14→- `docs/partner-guide/` - For teams integrating with Loop\n    15→\n    16→## Documentation Ownership\n    17→\n    18→- This file defines **repo-wide** coding agent defaults.\n    19→- App/package-specific behavior should be documented in local docs in that scope.\n    20→- For Bebop work, see `apps/bebop/CLAUDE.md` (automatically includes agent workflow and architecture standards).\n    21→\n    22→## Common Commands\n    23→\n    24→All commands run from repo root. Use `yarn`, not `npm run`. Lage automatically handles prerequisites (build, bundle).\n    25→\n    26→```bash\n    27→# Development\n    28→yarn                              # Install dependencies (run after git pull or branch switch)\n    29→yarn start --to loop-app          # Start Loop app dev server\n    30→yarn build --to <package-name>    # Build up to a specific package\n    31→yarn test --to <package-name>     # Run unit tests\n    32→yarn test:e2e --to <package-name> # Run Playwright e2e tests\n    33→yarn prettier --to <package-name> # Format code\n    34→yarn lint --to <package-name>     # Lint package\n    35→yarn lint --fix --to <package-name> # Lint and auto-fix\n    36→\n    37→# Single test (from package directory)\n    38→yarn test TestFileName.test.ts\n    39→yarn test --testNamePattern \"pattern\"\n    40→yarn test:e2e --file TestFileName.playwright-test.ts\n    41→\n    42→# Faster builds for targeted work\n    43→yarn build --since master         # Only packages changed since master\n    44→yarn test --since master          # Test only changed packages\n    45→yarn build --scope <package-name> # Build package AND all its consumers\n    46→\n    47→# Validation\n    48→yarn validate                     # Full validation (build, lint, test, e2e)\n    49→yarn validate:lint                # Lint-only (faster)\n    50→\n    51→# Maintenance\n    52→yarn clean                        # Clean build artifacts\n    53→yarn scrub                        # Full clean including node_modules\n    54→yarn change                       # Generate change files for PRs\n    55→```\n    56→\n    57→Full script list in `package.json`. See `docs/developer-guide/tooling/yarn-script-reference.md` for details.\n    58→\n    59→### Claude Code Commands\n    60→\n    61→```bash\n    62→/review-branch                    # Review changes on current branch\n    63→/create-pr                        # Create PR for office-bohemia\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→## Code Architecture\n    67→\n    68→### Directory Structure\n    69→\n    70→- `apps/` - Applications (loop-app, bebop, scriptor-pad, test-app)\n    71→- `packages/` - ~200 shared packages\n    72→- `tools/` - Build tooling\n    73→- `azure/` - Deployment configurations\n    74→- `docs/` - Engineering documentation\n    75→\n    76→### Core Architectural Concepts\n    77→\n    78→**Loop Components** are portable, collaborative experiences (LEAP: Live, Embeddable, Actionable, Portable). They render in any M365 host.\n    79→\n    80→**Loop Hosts** are applications that embed Loop Components (Teams, Outlook, Word, Loop App).\n    81→\n    82→**Containers** are Fluid Framework containers - the collaborative data layer. Key containers:\n    83→\n    84→- `loop-page-container` - Powers Loop pages (canvas with Scriptor, Tablero, etc.)\n    85→- `office-fluid-container` - Powers inline Loop components in Teams/Outlook chat\n    86→\n    87→**WorkspaceComponent** (`apps/loop-app/src/WorkspaceComponent/`) is the embedding surface for hosts to render full Loop workspace/page experiences. Hosts like the M365 Copilot App use this to embed Loop experiences without running the full Loop App. Served at `/workspaceComponentManifest.json`.\n    88→\n    89→### Key Packages\n    90→\n    91→| Package | Purpose |\n    92→|---------|---------|\n    93→| `loop-app` | Loop web application (apps/) |\n    94→| `loop-page-container` | Fluid container for Loop pages |\n    95→| `office-fluid-container` | Fluid container for inline components |\n    96→| `scriptor` | Rich text editing engine |\n    97→| `tablero` / `tablero-views` | Table component |\n    98→| `component-ux` | Shared UI components |\n    99→| `loop-app-ux` | Loop app specific UX |\n   100→| `base-container` | Container utilities |\n   101→\n   102→### Testing Container Changes\n   103→\n   104→- **For loop-page-container**: Use `yarn start --to loop-page-container` (demo app at localhost:3000)\n   105→- **For Loop App**: Use `yarn start --to loop-app`\n   106→- **For Teams/Outlook integration**: Use `yarn localDeploy --to loop-page-container` with Fiddler rules (see package README)\n   107→\n   108→**Important**: Loop App bundles loop-page-container. Avoid PRs that span both - this can cause compatibility issues with hosts loading containers from CDN.\n   109→\n   110→## Code Style Guidelines\n   111→\n   112→### TypeScript\n   113→\n   114→- No `as` type assertions, `any` types, or `!` non-null assertions\n   115→- Use `?.` and `??` over traditional null checks\n   116→- Prefer immutable data (`const`, `readonly`)\n   117→\n   118→### React\n   119→\n   120→- Components must be pure (same inputs = same output)\n   121→- `useEffect` only for external systems (APIs, subscriptions, timers) - always include cleanup\n   122→- Never use `useEffect` for derived state\n   123→- Group related state: `useState({ x: 0, y: 0 })`\n   124→- Use status enums over multiple booleans: `'loading' | 'error' | 'success'`\n   125→- Use `useId()` for accessible IDs for components\n   126→\n   127→### Async Code\n   128→\n   129→- Prefer `async/await` over callbacks/promises\n   130→- Use `Promise.all` for parallel execution\n   131→- Avoid `setTimeout` as workaround for race conditions\n   132→\n   133→### Logging\n   134→\n   135→- Use provided logger instance, not `console.log`\n   136→- Log specific fields, not entire objects\n   137→\n   138→### API Design\n   139→\n   140→- Don't break public package APIs\n   141→- Prefer private over public methods/properties\n   142→- Pass optional params as objects, not multiple optional parameters\n   143→\n   144→## Azure DevOps CLI Setup\n   145→\n   146→Many skills/commands use Azure CLI to interact with Azure DevOps. One-time setup:\n   147→\n   148→1. Install Azure CLI: <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cli/azure/install-azure-cli>\n   149→2. Log in: `az login` (do NOT use `--use-device-code` — not supported by this org)\n   150→3. The shared prereq script (`.claude/scripts/az-prereqs.sh`) handles extension installation and default configuration automatically.\n   151→\n   152→If commands fail with auth errors, run `az login` again (tokens expire after ~60 minutes).\n   153→\n   154→## Testing\n   155→\n   156→- Unit tests: `*.test.ts`\n   157→- Mock all external dependencies\n   158→- Use `jest.useFakeTimers()` instead of real timers\n   159→- E2E tests: `*.playwright-test.ts` - Playwright-based\n   160→- Live tests: `yarn test:e2e:live` - Tests against real endpoints (staging/dogfood/prod)\n   161→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XrfUS8UeV8YDsw48sFBkQR","session_id":"8a2fc4e6-c1a3-49e6-ae99-e4ee481c1eee","uuid":"791f10d6-5ef4-45f5-beeb-415d89a41b3f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012CCT7JYKneobjLd4SN7h8e","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# CLAUDE.md\n     2→\n     3→@AGENTS.md\n     4→@CONTRIBUTING.md\n     5→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XrfUS8UeV8YDsw48sFBkQR","session_id":"8a2fc4e6-c1a3-49e6-ae99-e4ee481c1eee","uuid":"d8a5b155-fcaa-4ba6-b806-7b93249c8215"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VonNiaJNPYQfKnVccJSBCF","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Welcome to Bebop\n     2→\n     3→Developer onboarding, environment setup, query parameters, and operational runbook for `apps/bebop`.\n     4→\n     5→## Getting Started\n     6→\n     7→### Installation\n     8→\n     9→Install the dependencies:\n    10→\n    11→```bash\n    12→yarn\n    13→```\n    14→\n    15→### Development\n    16→\n    17→#### Step 1: [First Time Only] Setup SSL Certificates & Host Overrides for Dev Domain Support\n    18→\n    19→Choose the setup instructions based on your development environment:\n    20→\n    21→#### Option A: Codespaces Users\n    22→\n    23→❗**NOTE** This needs be done on the local machine or dev box which you will use to access the codespace and you may be prompted for administrator/sudo password.❗\n    24→\n    25→- Complete the [codespace setup instructions](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_git/office-bohemia?path=/docs/developer-guide/codespaces/index.md&version=GBmaster&_a=preview) to set up SSL certificates and configure host overrides on your system to access the app via `https://m365.cloud.dev.microsoft:3001/bebop`.\n    26→\n    27→- Force restart your codespace\n    28→  - Go to [GitHub Codespaces](https://github.com/codespaces/), find the `office-bohemia-codespaces`, force stop them and then reopen. ![Screenshot showing force stop and reopen options for codespaces](image-2.png)\n    29→\n    30→#### Option B: Non-Codespace Users\n    31→\n    32→If you're not using Codespaces and developing directly on a Dev Box or local machine, run this codespace setup tool directly **on that same machine**. We still do codespace-setup tool just to keep things consistent and have easier interoperability.\n    33→\n    34→❗**NOTE** You may be prompted for administrator/sudo password.❗\n    35→\n    36→- Execute below commands from repo root\n    37→\n    38→  ```bash\n    39→  yarn build --to codespace-setup\n    40→  node ./packages/codespace-setup/lib/start.js\n    41→  ```\n    42→\n    43→#### Post-Setup (All Users)\n    44→\n    45→- If prompted, allow Pop-up & redirects on `https://m365.cloud.dev.microsoft:3001`\n    46→- If you had setup Bebop specific Requestly rules before, please remove them before proceeding further.\n    47→\n    48→#### Step 2: Start the development server with HMR\n    49→\n    50→```bash\n    51→yarn dev\n    52→```\n    53→\n    54→Your application will be available at `https://m365.cloud.dev.microsoft:3001`. (**NOTE**: DO NOT ACCESS THE APPLICATION THROUGH localhost URL)\n    55→\n    56→## Building for Production\n    57→\n    58→- Run bebop build from repo root to build all dependencies\n    59→\n    60→  ```bash\n    61→  yarn build --to bebop\n    62→  ```\n    63→\n    64→- Run bundle from `/apps/bebop/` path\n    65→\n    66→  ```bash\n    67→  yarn bundle\n    68→  ```\n    69→\n    70→## Running Production Build\n    71→\n    72→Run the production server from `/apps/bebop/` path. You could do it two ways,\n    73→\n    74→- With a local NodeJS reverse proxy substituting the C# .Net proxy\n    75→\n    76→  ```bash\n    77→  yarn start:local\n    78→  ```\n    79→\n    80→- Without a Node.js reverse proxy. You need to run the C# .Net proxy to supply auth\n    81→\n    82→  ```bash\n    83→  yarn start\n    84→  ```\n    85→\n    86→## Pre-PR Validation\n    87→\n    88→Before creating a PR, you can run the `prepare-bebop-for-pr` Claude Code skill to catch common CI failures quickly:\n    89→\n    90→```text\n    91→/prepare-bebop-for-pr\n    92→```\n    93→\n    94→This runs targeted validation scoped to Bebop packages — branch checks, merge conflict detection, build, lint, prettier, unit tests, and CONTRIBUTING.md alignment review — without running `yarn validate` across the entire monorepo. See [.claude/skills/prepare-bebop-for-pr/SKILL.md](../../.claude/skills/prepare-bebop-for-pr/SKILL.md) for details.\n    95→\n    96→## Architecture Review\n    97→\n    98→For PRs with significant Bebop changes, run the architecture review skill to check for violations across performance measurement, SSR integrity, client minimalism, streaming pipeline, web platform usage, intent-based loading, and React 19 compliance:\n    99→\n   100→```text\n   101→/review-bebop-architecture <PR-number-or-branch-name>\n   102→```\n   103→\n   104→This reviews the diff against 7 architectural focus areas (4 Critical, 2 High, 1 Medium), incorporates the `office-fluid` bot's bundle size data, and can post findings directly as PR comments. See [.claude/skills/review-bebop-architecture/SKILL.md](../../.claude/skills/review-bebop-architecture/SKILL.md) for details.\n   105→\n   106→## Understanding TanStack Composite Components\n   107→\n   108→Composite Components is the TanStack approach to building React Server Components (RSC) applications. It provides a powerful and flexible way to create modern web applications by leveraging the benefits of server-side rendering and component-based architecture.\n   109→\n   110→Learn more about React Server Components with TanStack Start in the [TanStack Start documentation](https://tanstack.com/start) and [TanStack Composite Components](https://tanstack.com/blog/composite-components).\n   111→\n   112→## Dev Tools\n   113→\n   114→Enable the TanStack DevTools and React Scan:\n   115→\n   116→- Add `?enableDevTools=true` to the URL.\n   117→- [TanStack DevTools](https://tanstack.com/devtools) appears in the UI with panels for Performance Metrics, TanStack Router, and TanStack Query.\n   118→- [React Scan](https://react-scan.com/) loads separately and shows the render-tracking toolbar.\n   119→\n   120→## Bundle Analysis\n   121→\n   122→Bundle analysis reports are generated automatically during every build. To analyze bundle sizes and identify optimization opportunities:\n   123→\n   124→1. Build from repo root:\n   125→\n   126→  ```bash\n   127→  yarn build --to bebop\n   128→  ```\n   129→\n   130→1. Run bundle analyzer from `/apps/bebop/` path to bundle and automatically open the reports in your browser:\n   131→\n   132→   ```bash\n   133→   yarn bundle:analyzer\n   134→   ```\n   135→\n   136→The report shows gzip and brotli sizes for each module, helping you identify:\n   137→\n   138→- Large dependencies that could be lazy-loaded\n   139→- Duplicate packages\n   140→- Unexpected transitive dependencies\n   141→\n   142→For a quick CLI summary of the largest chunks:\n   143→\n   144→```bash\n   145→cat apps/bebop/releaseDeployment/client/bundleStats.json | jq -r '.assets[] | select(.name | endswith(\".js\")) | \"\\(.size)\\t\\(.name)\"' | sort -rn | head -20\n   146→```\n   147→\n   148→## Environment Configuration\n   149→\n   150→Bebop uses different environment configurations depending on the context:\n   151→\n   152→### Local Development & Testing (This Repo)\n   153→\n   154→Environment files in `apps/bebop/`:\n   155→\n   156→- `.env.development` - Development mode (yarn dev)\n   157→- `.env.production` - Production mode defaults (yarn start)\n   158→\n   159→These files are loaded by `dotenv-flow` in [src/server.ts](./src/server.ts).\n   160→\n   161→### Deployed Environments (M365CopilotAppService Repo)\n   162→\n   163→Production deployments use configuration from the `M365CopilotAppService` repository:\n   164→\n   165→- `CosmicDeploy/BebopApp/.env.server.official` - Official deployment\n   166→- `CosmicDeploy/BebopApp/.env.server.unofficial` - Unofficial/test deployment\n   167→- `CosmicDeploy/BebopApp/appsettings.bebop.*.json` - .NET server settings\n   168→\n   169→**Note**: The `.env*` files in office-bohemia are NOT used in production deployments. They are only for local development and testing.\n   170→\n   171→## Deployment\n   172→\n   173→### Pipelines\n   174→\n   175→| Server Build Pipeline                                                                    | Release Pipeline                                                                           | Deployment Endpoints                                                                                                            |\n   176→| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n   177→| [M365 Copilot App Official](https://dev.azure.com/office/OC/_build?definitionId=36060)   | [M365 Copilot App Release](https://dev.azure.com/office/OC/_build?definitionId=36083)      | [WUS2-SDF1](https://office-home-m365copilotapp.wus2sdf1.office-home-m365copilotapp.westus2-sdf.cosmic-ppe.office.net/bebop/)    |\n   178→| [M365 Copilot App Unofficial](https://dev.azure.com/office/OC/_build?definitionId=36171) | [M365 Copilot App Release Test](https://dev.azure.com/office/OC/_build?definitionId=36113) | [WUS2-TEST1](https://office-home-m365copilotapp.wus2test1.office-home-m365copilotapp.westus2-test.cosmic-int.office.net/bebop/) |\n   179→\n   180→### Bebop CDN\n   181→\n   182→During deployment, Bebop client assets are published to 1CDN in the `M365CopilotAppService` [pipelines](https://dev.azure.com/office/OC/_build?definitionScope=%5CM365%20Office%20Home%20Service%5CM365%20Copilot%20App%20Service). We use the [officehub CDN](https://eng.ms/docs/experiences-devices/global-experiences-platform/office-india/experiences/m365-office-home-service/officecom/developer-guide/architecture-overview/1cdn/1cdn) storage container.\n   183→\n   184→#### CDN Endpoints\n   185→\n   186→| office-bohemia build                                                                   | Server build                                                                             | CDN Base Url                                                  |\n   187→| -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |\n   188→| [office-bohemia CI](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_build?definitionId=8228)       | [M365 Copilot App Official](https://dev.azure.com/office/OC/_build?definitionId=36060)   | `https://res.cdn.office.net/officehub/bebop/versionless`      |\n   189→| [office-bohemia CI or PR](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_build?definitionId=8228) | [M365 Copilot App Unofficial](https://dev.azure.com/office/OC/_build?definitionId=36171) | `https://res-sdf.cdn.office.net/officehub/bebop/versionless/` |\n   190→\n   191→#### Running locally with CDN\n   192→\n   193→By default in development mode (`yarn dev`), all assets are served locally.\n   194→\n   195→For production builds (`yarn start` or `yarn start:local`):\n   196→\n   197→- **Default**: Serves assets locally (no CDN) - works out of the box\n   198→- **Test with CDN**: Add `BEBOP_CDN_BASE_URL` to test CDN behavior\n   199→- **Deployed environments**: Use config from M365CopilotAppService repo (not .env files from office-bohemia)\n   200→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XrfUS8UeV8YDsw48sFBkQR","session_id":"8a2fc4e6-c1a3-49e6-ae99-e4ee481c1eee","uuid":"6a59312f-d19e-447a-a81d-11865b95a851"}
