{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ASzKJ9RvxMJfsVbgagoWUd","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# WebSocket Module\n     2→\n     3→This directory contains all WebSocket-related functionality organized in a clean, modular routing architecture.\n     4→\n     5→## Overview\n     6→\n     7→This implementation provides a simple, extensible WebSocket routing system that allows multiple protocol handlers to coexist without conflicts. Perfect for adding Anthropic API proxy, MCP calls, and other protocols.\n     8→\n     9→## Structure\n    10→\n    11→```\n    12→websocket/\n    13→├── index.ts               # Main entry point - exports all public APIs\n    14→├── core/                  # Core WebSocket infrastructure\n    15→│   ├── router.ts          # Message routing system\n    16→│   └── server-handler.ts  # Global WebSocket connection handler\n    17→└── handlers/              # Protocol-specific handlers\n    18→    ├── llm-proxy-handler.ts # LLM API proxy handler\n    19→    └── mcp.ts             # Model Context Protocol handler\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→## Architecture Components\n    23→\n    24→### 1. `core/router.ts` - Simple Global Router\n    25→**Role**: Routes WebSocket messages to appropriate handlers\n    26→- Single global router that dispatches messages by `type` field\n    27→- Handlers register for specific message types\n    28→- Clean separation of concerns\n    29→\n    30→### 2. `core/server-handler.ts` - Global WebSocket Handler\n    31→**Role**: Sets up WebSocket server with routing\n    32→- Single point for all WebSocket connections\n    33→- Routes incoming messages through the global router\n    34→- Handles connection lifecycle\n    35→\n    36→### 3. Protocol Handlers (e.g., `handlers/llm-proxy-handler.ts`)\n    37→**Role**: Handle specific protocol logic\n    38→- Register message handlers with the global router\n    39→- Set up HTTP endpoints for their protocol\n    40→- Process messages of their registered types\n    41→\n    42→## Message Flow\n    43→\n    44→1. **WebSocket Client** → Sends message with `type` field\n    45→2. **Global WebSocket Handler** → Receives raw message\n    46→3. **WebSocket Router** → Routes to appropriate handler based on `message.type`\n    47→4. **Protocol Handler** → Processes message and sends response\n    48→\n    49→## Usage\n    50→\n    51→```typescript\n    52→// Import everything you need from the main entry point\n    53→import {\n    54→  setupGlobalWebSocketHandler,\n    55→  registerLLMProxyHandlers,\n    56→  registerMCPHandlers\n    57→} from './websocket';\n    58→\n    59→// Setup is clean and simple\n    60→setupGlobalWebSocketHandler(wss);\n    61→registerLLMProxyHandlers(app, getWsClient);\n    62→registerMCPHandlers(app, getWsClient);\n    63→```\n    64→\n    65→## Adding New Protocol Handlers\n    66→\n    67→New protocols can easily be extended:\n    68→\n    69→```typescript\n    70→// handlers/new-protocol.ts\n    71→import { wsRouter } from '../core/router';\n    72→\n    73→function handleMyProtocol(message: any, ws: WebSocket): boolean {\n    74→  if (message.type !== 'my_protocol_request') return false;\n    75→\n    76→  // Handle the message\n    77→  console.log('Handling my protocol:', message);\n    78→\n    79→  // Send response\n    80→  ws.send(JSON.stringify({\n    81→    id: message.id,\n    82→    type: 'my_protocol_response',\n    83→    result: 'success'\n    84→  }));\n    85→\n    86→  return true;\n    87→}\n    88→\n    89→export function registerMyProtocolHandlers(app: Application, getWsClient: () => WebSocket | null) {\n    90→  // Register with global router\n    91→  wsRouter.registerHandler('my_protocol_request', handleMyProtocol);\n    92→  wsRouter.registerHandler('my_protocol_response', handleMyProtocol);\n    93→\n    94→  // Add HTTP endpoints if needed\n    95→  app.post('/my-protocol', (req, res) => {\n    96→    // HTTP to WebSocket logic\n    97→  });\n    98→}\n    99→```\n   100→\n   101→**Steps to add a new handler:**\n   102→1. Create a new handler file in `handlers/`\n   103→2. Import and use `wsRouter` from `../core/router`\n   104→3. Export your registration function\n   105→4. Add the export to `index.ts`\n   106→5. Register in your main application\n   107→\n   108→## Current Handlers\n   109→\n   110→### Core Handlers\n   111→- **LLM Proxy**: Handles `llm_request`, `llm_response*` messages - Anthropic API proxy\n   112→- **MCP Handler**: Handles `mcp_request`, `mcp_response` messages - Model Context Protocol\n   113→\n   114→### Search Handlers\n   115→- **Enterprise Search**: Handles enterprise content search requests\n   116→- **Enterprise File Search**: Handles `enterprise_file_search_result_item`, `enterprise_file_search_response` messages - Streaming file search with automatic storage\n   117→- **Enterprise Chat Search**: Handles `enterprise_chat_search_response` messages - Teams chat search with automatic storage\n   118→- **Web Search**: Handles web search requests\n   119→- **Web Fetch**: Handles webpage content fetching\n   120→\n   121→### Media Handlers\n   122→- **Image Search**: Handles `image_search_result_item`, `image_search_response` messages - Streaming image search with automatic storage\n   123→\n   124→## Key Benefits\n   125→\n   126→- **Simple**: Minimal overhead, easy to understand\n   127→- **Extensible**: New handlers just register their message types\n   128→- **Isolated**: Handlers don't interfere with each other\n   129→- **Maintainable**: Clear separation of concerns\n   130→\n   131→This architecture scales well and makes it easy for multiple team members to add different protocol handlers without conflicts.\n   132→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01D1btGNgUTxKhKd2oyCp7xP","session_id":"8a2fc4e6-c1a3-49e6-ae99-e4ee481c1eee","uuid":"9c264a79-a365-4857-b8a9-a4ecbc701bde"}
